The truth is always more nuanced, of course, though in some cases it=E2=80=
=99s also more simple. As every veteran of this industry knows, almost no o=
ne gives up the anchor chair of their own volition: not Hoda Kotb, who only=
 determined she=E2=80=99d reached =E2=80=9Cthe top of the wave=E2=80=9D at =
NBC=E2=80=99s Today show after learning that she=E2=80=99d be asked to take=
 a pay cut ( https://puck.news/what-hoda-kotbs-today-show-departure-means-f=
or-the-star-anchor-era/?1731534460&utm_campaign=3DIn+The+Room+-+SUBSCRIBERS=
+%2811%2F13%2F24%29&utm_content=3DIn+The+Room+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2810%2F2%2F24%=
29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da=
42abd12a ); not Norah O=E2=80=99Donnell, whose desire to pursue more Pope F=
rancis-style interview specials was spurred on by CBS=E2=80=99s perplexing =
decision
to dispense with ( https://puck.news/anchors-away/?utm_campaign=3DIn+The+Ro=
om+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2811%2F13%2F24%29&utm_content=3DIn+The+Room+-+SUBSCRIBERS=
+%2810%2F2%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_t=
erm=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) a star-led strategy at Evening News; and certain=
ly not Chris Wallace. Yes, everyone wants to spend more time with their fam=
ilies or write new chapters. But, as a wise media executive once told me, =
=E2=80=9Cthey also don=E2=80=99t want to work for less money even though th=
ey have already made a fortune.=E2=80=9D

In Wallace=E2=80=99s case, CNN C.E.O. Mark Thompson was planning to cancel =
both of his shows: Who=E2=80=99s Talking to Chris Wallace, the weekly inter=
view series that was originally supposed to air on CNN+ and now airs on Max=
=E2=80=94until Friday, when it will air its final episode=E2=80=94and the S=
aturday morning panel discussion program, The Chris Wallace Show. Instead, =
Thompson and Entelis intended to offer Wallace a new role as an analyst, wh=
ich would have
resulted in a significantly diminished compensation package and, presumably=
, far less air time. The CNN leaders conveyed that news to Wallace=E2=80=99=
s agents, though Wallace maintains that he never engaged in any discussions=
 about a future role because he=E2=80=99d already set his course. =E2=80=9C=
It doesn=E2=80=99t matter what was or wasn=E2=80=99t said in that meeting b=
ecause I had already decided with my wife six months ago to leave CNN,=E2=
=80=9D Wallace told me in a text message. =E2=80=9CAny further speculation =
is irrelevant.=E2=80=9D

Regardless, Thompson=E2=80=99s decision to cancel his shows was obviously t=
he right one. The most recent broadcast of The Chris Wallace Show drew 450,=
000 viewers and just 85,000 in the advertiser-coveted 25-to-54-year-old dem=
o=E2=80=94an audience size at which it=E2=80=99s increasingly hard to justi=
fy most of the talent salaries at CNN. While the network will continue to h=
andsomely compensate its major franchise players=E2=80=94Jake Tapper isn=E2=
=80=99t going anywhere, for
instance=E2=80=94it will need to be more creative, and more frugal, when it=
 comes to highly compensated commentators like Wallace. Ever the diplomat, =
Thompson issued a graceful statement on Monday calling the former Fox News =
Sunday host =E2=80=9Cone of the most respected political journalists in the=
 news business.=E2=80=9D

As I reported last week, Thompson is on the verge of implementing a new rou=
nd of layoffs that will target hundreds of employees, after which he plans =
to create new positions on the digital side of the business. Inevitably, th=
ose cuts will include some high-priced TV talent, as well. Wallace would li=
ke the world to believe that he got out before the storm hit. In truth, he =
was one of its first and most obvious casualties.

